 undergraduates are being exploited as a low-cost, disposable workforce. Marc Bousquet, a major figure in the academic labor movement, exposes the seamy underbelly of higher education—a world where faculty, graduate students, and undergraduates work long hours for fast-food wages. Assessing the costs of higher education's corporatization on faculty and students at every level, How the University Works is urgent reading for anyone interested in the fate of the university.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCollege teachersxSalaries, etczUnited States. 0aCollege teachersxSalaries, etc.zUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxEmployeesxSalaries, etczUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxEmployeesxSalaries, etc.zUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aNelson, Cary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNelson, Cary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479974140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814789926.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789926423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814789926/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK